Thanks ARD, I appreciate the kind words. :)

+Hinterkaifeck

-Hide




My only gripe is that you couldn't fit the Hinterkaifeck murders into this in any way
附加记录：    

I'm curious as to how the article reminded you of the Hinterkaifeck murders - was it just the general atmosphere, or did you find the details of some of the murders similar?

What's funny about your comment is that the literal inspiration for this skip was the Hinterkaifeck murders. I read a lot of true crime (mostly historical murders and serial killers) so I've known about those for a long time, but a few years back I read a more in-depth article about the murders and that's when I had the idea for this skip. The idea to base this skip on Santa Claus/Krampus came later (IIRC, because one of the most tantalizing clues about the murders had to do with snow, I ended up associating them with Christmas), but at its core the skip is about a historical, anomalous serial killer.

As to why I didn't make an explicit reference to the Hinterkaifeck murders in the skip, there are a few reasons for that. For one, I felt the details about those murders weren't weird enough to be the Yule Man's handiwork - essentially, the Hinterkaifeck victims were all bludgeoned with a mattock, which, as horrible as that is, doesn't really fit the Yule Man's more elaborate, pagan-themed M.O. I also wasn't sure I could find a way to include the actual murders without disrespecting the victims and their ordeal (not saying it's impossible, though). I'm also aware that there's already an SCP on the site dealing with the Hinterkaifeck murders, though I haven't had the chance to read it yet, and I didn't want to retread the same ground. And finally, the Hinterkaifeck murders happened in March, which, once I'd settled on the idea of a Christmas-themed SCP, made it pretty much impossible to use them in the article.

However, the Hinterkaifeck murders are still very much the soul of this article. The most obvious reference to them is my account of the third Weissnacht Event in the log, which has the family being murdered in a stable (the real murders happened in a barn), in a small German village. I also mention that the farm animals were not harmed (there was evidence that the real Hinterkaifeck killer actually fed the animals in the barn before leaving after the murders), and that footsteps were found in the snow in the days preceding the murder (which also happened before the real murders). The general behavior of the Yule Man is also consistent with that of the Hinterkaifeck killer: the stalking of the families over the days preceding a murder, the fact that he attacks them in their beds at night and kills them in view of each other (which seems to be what happened with the Hinterkaifeck murders). Just reading about the details of how they found the bodies in the barn and how one girl had survived for several hours surrounded by her family's corpses (they found she had pulled out clumps of her own hair in anguish or agony), is what really drove home for me how horrifying this must have been for the family, and what pushed me to write an article about the murder of entire families. Even the term  was chosen because it was a German word, in reference those murders.

With all that said, I'm still open to changing the article, so if you have some idea of how I could include the actual murders into this, I'd certainly take it into consideration. Thanks for your comment! :)








